h and Swinnerton-Dyer Conjecture and the Main Conjecture of Iwasawa Theory. Because Selmer groups play a central role in Arithmetic Algebraic Geometry, Euler systems should be a powerful tool in the future development of the field. Here, in the first book to appear on the subject, Karl Rubin presents a self-contained development of the theory of Euler systems. Rubin first reviews and develops the necessary facts from Galois cohomology. He then introduces Euler systems, states the main theorems, and develops examples and applications. The remainder of the book is devoted to the proofs of the main theorems as well as some further speculations. The book assumes a solid background in algebraic Number Theory, and is suitable as an advanced graduate text. As a research monograph it will also prove useful to number theorists and researchers in Arithmetic Algebraic Geometry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAlgebraic number theory. 0ap-adic numbers. 7aMATHEMATICS / Number Theory.2bisacsh  aAbelian extension.  aAbelian variety.  aAbsolute Galois group.  aAlgebraic closure.  aBarry Mazur.  aBig O notation.  aBirch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture.  aCardinality.  aClass field theory.  aCoefficient.  aCohomology.  aComplex multiplication.  aConjecture.  aCorollary.  aCyclotomic field.  aDimension (vector space).  aDivisibility rule.  aEigenvalues and eigenvectors.  aElliptic curve.  aError term.  aEuler product.  aEuler system.  aExact sequence.  aExistential quantification.  aField of fractions.  aFinite set.  aFunctional equation.  aGalois cohomology.  aGalois group.  aGalois module.  aGauss sum.  aGlobal field.  aHeegner point.  aIdeal class group.  aInteger.  aInverse limit.  aInverse system.  aKarl Rubin.  aLocal field.  aMathematical induction.